Actually, I'm remembering now why it works this way, and I understand the problem you're getting at.  We actually did this on purpose, because an implementation pattern that came up a couple times was:

1. Dbus Interface changes, and adds new property of a type that the consumer interfaces interface had never seen before.
2. All GetAll unpacks immediately start failing, including those that currently ignore the new property, simply because there was no way to unpack it.

For that reason, we did the default construct variant thing.  You're right, it's non-ideal, but in practice, the above pattern is guaranteed to cause a bug, whereas the pattern we have now is unlikely, although possible to cause a bug.

Yes, monostate might be a way to make that better, but that would involve either option 1 or option 2 above (or whatever ideas you have).  If you're interested in one of those, lets get this patchset updated with something that compiles and go from there to see if it's better.

Not sure this is the right solution. See man shadow(5):

> account expiration date
>     The date of expiration of the account, expressed as the number of days since Jan 1, 1970.
>     ...
>     The value 0 should not be used as it is interpreted as either an account with no expiration, or as an expiration on Jan 1, 1970.

And also usermod(8):

> Note: if you wish to lock the account (not only access with a password), you should also set the EXPIRE_DATE to 1.

Unfortunately, there is ambiguity about what it means to have an expiration date of 0. It would be kind of silly if there was no way to disable accounts on January 1, 1970, so I'm not surprised if the utilities actually work as you expect. But please at least add a comment to the code about this discrepancy and that it's verified to work.

From the man page, it seems setting expire date to 0 is an implementation-defined behavior. Maybe some implementation take 0 as never expire and some of them taka it as expire on 1970-01-01.

In libpam 1.3.1 (OpenBMC is now using), 0 means expire on 1970-01-01.

> curdays = (long int)(time(NULL) / (60 * 60 * 24));
> D(("today is %d, last change %d", curdays, spent->sp_lstchg));
> if ((curdays >= spent->sp_expire) && (spent->sp_expire != -1)) {
> 	D(("account expired"));
> 	return PAM_ACCT_EXPIRED;
> }

"sp_expire" is from glibc function "getspnam(username)" which reads and parses entry in /etc/shadow by username. The source code is pretty hard to read, so I wrote a simple program to test it. Below it the conclusion

> User never expire: sp_expire == -1
> User expire on [date]: sp_expire == [date] - "1970-01-01"

So setting the EXPIRE_DATE to 0 is reasonable in OpenBMC. Anyway, I will add a comment in the code.
